 for bestpractices and # Cronjobs Engine

## Overview
Build a first-class Cronjobs Engine within LifeOps that defines, schedules, executes, and audits agent/workflow runs. Each cronjob is a fully modeled object with scheduling (cron expression or builder), timezone-awareness, trigger types (time/event/conditional), input templating, permissions & automation level, constraints and safety rails, retry policy with backoff and dead-letter handling, run recording, and artifact/log traces. The system provides a centralized dashboard for management, a detailed Run Details page for per-run inspection and reversibility, and a full-featured Cronjob Editor for creating and editing cronjobs. All components enforce rigorous runtime safety, validation, auditing, and secure access control.

---

## Components to Build

1) Cronjobs Dashboard (page_cronjobs_list_007)
- Purpose: List, search, filter, enable/disable, bulk actions, scheduling quick-create, and schedule builder.
- Key features:
  - Fast search across cronjob name, target, status, last run outcome.
  - Filters: enabled/paused, next run time window, trigger type, target type (agent vs workflow), automation level, and spend/budget constraints.
  - Bulk actions: enable/disable, delete, clone, update permissions, update timezones or schedules for a batch.
  - Schedule Builder: interactive UI for composing cron expressions or selecting UI builder presets with timezone selection.
  - Per-row actions: view details, quick edit, clone, run now, pause/resume, edit, delete.
  - Next run display, last run outcome badge, and quick stats (count of runs in last 24h).
  - Create New Cronjob button leading to Cronjob Editor (page_cronjob_editor_008).
- Data considerations:
  - Show cronjob name, target, schedule, nextRunAt, enabled, lastRun, outcome, retriesPending.
  - Ensure data ingestion uses data ?? [] and map through safely: (cronjobs ?? []).map(...).

2) Cronjob Editor (page_cronjob_editor_008)
- Purpose: Full editor for cronjob objects with all fields and validation.
- Fields:
  - Name: string, unique per workspace.
  - Schedule: cron expression or UI builder (e.g., time windows, intervals); supports timezone-aware selection.
  - Timezone: IANA timezone string; default to user locale.
  - Trigger Type: Time, Event, Conditional.
  - Target: Agent or Workflow Template; optional fallback.
  - Input Payload Template: templated prompts with variable bindings; supports defaults and mustache/handlebars-like syntax.
  - Permissions & Automation Level: suggest-only, approval-required, conditional auto-execute, bounded autopilot.
  - Constraints: max actions per run, max spend per run, allowed tools/services.
  - Safety Rails: required confirmations, irreversible actions, hard stops.
  - Retry Policy: max retries, backoff strategy (exponential, linear), max backoff, dead-letter handling (target queue or storage).
  - Outputs Configuration: what to capture (run history, logs, artifacts, diffs, traces), retention policy.
  - Advanced: audit scope, memory/state sharing, memory scope across agent interactions.
- Interactions:
  - Real-time validation with immediate feedback; show validation errors in-line.
  - Schedule preview: show next N run times in the chosen timezone.
  - Press Save to persist; Cancel to discard changes with a confirmation if unsaved.
- Validation and safety:
  - Ensure schedule is valid cron or builder configuration.
  - Validate input template variables exist in the scope and have defaults.
  - Validate that target exists and is accessible by the current user/role.
  - Enforce runtime safety constraints at save time (e.g., cannot enable if safety rails incomplete).

3) Run Details Page (page_run_details_010)
- Purpose: Detailed information about a single cron/agent run.
- Sections:
  - Meta header: cronjob name, runId, status (Scheduled, Running, Completed, Failed, Reverted), timestamps (scheduledAt, startedAt, endedAt), duration, retries used.
  - Inputs: resolved input payload with variable substitutions (show redacted if sensitive).
  - Agent-to-Agent Message Trace: trace of messages between agents, with a DAG-like expandable view; show sender/receiver, timestamp, payload snippet.
  - Logs: aggregated logs with filtering by level (info, warn, error), searchable; allow tail view and pause/resume of log stream for live runs.
  - Diffs: visual diffs of input vs output payloads, prompts, and responses; highlight changes.
  - Artifacts: artifacts produced by the run (files, reports, generated outputs); provide preview/download.
  - Timing: per-step timing breakdown, bottlenecks, and latency visualization (timeline or Gantt-like view).
  - Outcome: final status, success metrics, costs, ROI estimation, and any errors.
  - Revert Actions: ability to revert specific actions within the run with an audit trail, including contextual confirmations.
- Interactions:
  - Click-to-expand trace nodes, search within logs, filter artifacts by type, download artifacts.
  - Revert button per actionable step with confirmation and rollback summary.
- Safety/risk:
  - Ensure no direct execution or re-run without required approvals if the parent cronjob has an approval workflow.

4) Cronjobs Engine Core (Backend services)
- Time/cron scheduler:
  - Support cron expressions and a UI builder; timezone-aware scheduling with IANA timezones.
  - Use a robust scheduling engine (e.g., node-cron, Quartz-like system, or a dedicated scheduler) with drift-correction and checkpointing.
  - Trigger types: Time, Event, Conditional. Event/Conditional should be pluggable adapters (e.g., external webhook events, internal condition evaluations).
- Input templating engine:
  - Template language supporting variables, defaults, and scope; secure evaluation with sandboxed execution.
  - Bindings to runtime scope (workspace, cronjob, agent capabilities, secrets).
- Permission model:
  - Automation level definitions: suggest-only, approval-required, conditional auto-execute, bounded autopilot.
  - Access control per cronjob; enforce restrictions during run initiation.
- Constraints enforcement:
  - max actions per run, spend per run, allowed tools; enforce at runtime and/or preflight checks.
- Safety rails:
  - Mandatory confirmations for dangerous actions; configurable per cronjob.
- Retry policy:
  - Backoff strategy (exponential/linear), max retries, dead-letter route (to DLQ or alerting channel).
- Run recording:
  - Persist run history, logs, traces, diffs, artifacts, and errors; provide immutable audit trail.
- API surface:
  - CRUD for cronjobs; initiate runs manually; pause/resume; clone; update schedules; fetch run details; query artifacts/logs.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend

- Architecture:
  - TypeScript React with a modular component library aligned to LifeOps design system.
  - State management via React Context or a lightweight store (Redux/Zustand) with selectors for cronjob lists, runs, and editor state.
  - Accessibility: aria-labels, keyboard navigation, and focus management.
- Components and UI:
  - Cronjobs List Table:
    - Columns: Enabled toggle, Name, Target, Schedule (with next run), Trigger Type, Last Run, Next Run, Actions.
    - Row-level controls: enable/disable switch, quick edit, clone, delete, run now.
    - Bulk actions bar with multi-select checkboxes and batch operations.
  - Schedule Builder:
    - Interactive cron builder with presets for common schedules (every minute, hourly, daily at time, weekdays).
    - Timezone selector; show human-friendly next-run preview.
  - Cronjob Editor Form:
    - Multi-section layout with left navigation for sections: General, Schedule, Target, Input, Permissions, Constraints, Safety, Retry, Outputs.
    - Real-time validation; inline hints; summary of changes.
  - Run Details Panel:
    - Tabbed sections: Inputs, Trace, Logs, Diffs, Artifacts, Timing, Outcome, Revert Actions.
    - Trace visualization: collapsible tree with hop-by-hop messages, timestamps.
    - Logs viewer with search, filter by level, and export option.
    - Artifacts gallery with previews/downloads.
  - Modals/Dialogs:
    - Confirm destructive actions (delete, disable with pending runs, irreversible revert steps).
    - Approvals queue integration prompts for runs requiring review.
- Data handling:
  - Ensure all arrays from API calls are guarded: (data ?? []) and Array.isArray checks where applicable.
  - Initialize useState hooks with proper typing: useState<YourType[]>([]) for arrays; ensure default values are non-null.
  - API responses: validate shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Optional chaining for deeply nested API responses.
- Performance:
  - Debounced search, pagination, and infinite scrolling where appropriate.
  - Memoization for expensive render paths (e.g., large run traces).
- Security:
  - Don’t expose secrets in the payload previews; redact sensitive fields by default with an option to reveal for authorized users.
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for utility functions (templating engine, validation rules).
  - Integration tests for API surface (create/update/run/pause/clone).
  - E2E tests for core user flows: create cronjob, schedule run, view run details, revert action.

### Backend

- Data Models (design to be implemented in DB):
  - Cronjob
    - id, workspaceId, name, description, enabled (boolean), paused (boolean), scheduleType (cron|builder), cronExpression (nullable), builderConfig (JSON), timezone, triggerType (time|event|conditional), targetType (agent|workflow), targetId, inputTemplate (JSON), scope (JSON), permissions (JSON), automationLevel (enum), constraints (JSON), safetyRails (JSON), retryPolicy (JSON), outputsConfig (JSON), createdAt, updatedAt, nextRunAt, lastRunAt, lastRunStatus.
  - Run
    - id, cronjobId, runNumber, scheduledAt, startedAt, endedAt, durationMs, status (Scheduled|Running|Completed|Failed|Reverted), retryCount, maxRetries, resultSummary (JSON), logsRef, traceRef, artifactsRef, inputsRef, diffsRef, errors (array), createdAt.
  - RunLog, RunTrace, RunArtifact, etc. (normalized or blob-backed depending on storage).
  - TraceMessage
    - id, runId, sender, receiver, timestamp, payloadSnippet, direction.
  - Artifact
    - id, runId, type, name, size, url, preview.
  - Event/AdapterRegistry
    - For Event triggers and external/internal condition adapters.
- APIs:
  - POST /cronjobs: create cronjob
  - GET /cronjobs: list with filters, pagination
  - GET /cronjobs/{id}: detail
  - PUT /cronjobs/{id}: update
  - PATCH /cronjobs/{id}: partial update (enable/disable, schedule, target, etc.)
  - DELETE /cronjobs/{id}: delete
  - POST /cronjobs/{id}/clone: clone cronjob
  - POST /cronjobs/{id}/run: trigger immediate run
  - POST /cronjobs/{id}/pause: pause
  - POST /cronjobs/{id}/resume: resume
  - GET /cronjobs/{id}/runs: list runs
  - GET /cronjobs/{id}/runs/{runId}: run detail
  - GET /runs/{runId}/logs, /runs/{runId}/trace, /runs/{runId}/artifacts
  - POST /runs/{runId}/revert/{actionId}: revert specific action
- Scheduling Engine:
  - Durable scheduler with persistence; supports time drift correction.
  - Event and Conditional triggers must be pluggable with a registry and capability checks.
- Input Templating Engine:
  - Template evaluation safe sandbox; supports binding to workspace, cronjob, run context.
- Validation:
  - Centralized validation logic for cron expressions, timezones, target existence, permissions, quotas.
- Security:
  - Role-based access control; endpoints protected; audit logging of all mutation operations.
  - Input payload sanitization to prevent injections in templating and prompts.
- Storage/ETL:
  - Efficient storage of large run traces and artifacts; support object storage for artifacts with signed URLs.
- Observability:
  - Metrics for cronjob scheduling latency, run durations, success rates, retry counts.
  - Centralized logs per cronjob and run.

---

## Integration

- Data flow:
  - Frontend uses REST/GraphQL API to fetch cronjobs and runs; responses are guarded (data ?? []) and validated.
  - Scheduler runs cronjobs, creates Run records, captures inputs, traces, and artifacts; writes to Run, Logs, Trace, Artifacts stores.
  - Run details page reads Run, Logs, Trace, Artefacts via API with streaming where possible.
- Cross-service communication:
  - Agent orchestration layer handles agent-to-agent messages; trace IDs propagate through the Run to enable end-to-end traceability.
  - Approvals service queues actions requiring review; cronjobs fire only after approval if required.
- Security/Permissions:
  - Each API and UI action checks user permissions; ensure that only authorized users can modify sensitive cronjobs or view run details.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) Access Cronjobs Dashboard
- User lands on the Cronjobs Dashboard.
- Sees a searchable, filterable list with next run times and status badges.
- Uses search or filters to narrow down to enabled cronjobs for a given agent.
- Uses bulk actions to enable/disable or clone several cronjobs.

2) Create/Edit Cronjob via Editor
- User clicks Quick Create or Edit on a cronjob card.
- Editor loads with sections: General, Schedule, Target, Input, Permissions, Constraints, Safety Rails, Retry, Outputs.
- User fills in fields:
  - Name, Schedule: choose cron expression or builder, set timezone.
  - Trigger Type, Target: select agent or workflow.
  - Input Template: draft payload with variables; system validates required vars.
  - Permissions & Automation: select appropriate level.
  - Constraints & Safety: set limits; configure mandatory confirmations.
  - Retry Policy & Outputs: configure dead-letter, retention, and artifacts.
- Validation highlights issues in real time; Next Run preview updates.
- User saves; UI shows lifecycle toast; cronjob is created/updated.
- If scheduled runs exist, the dashboard updates with nextRunAt accordingly.

3) Run a Cronjob or Observe Runs
- User can trigger Run Now from dashboard or editor.
- Run is created; run details page can be opened to monitor progress.
- On Run Details, user inspects inputs, trace, logs, diffs, artifacts, timing, and outcome.
- If needed, user can revert specific actions from the Run Details page with proper confirmations.

4) Run Details Exploration
- User expands trace to view inter-agent messages; filters by level in logs; previews diffs and artifacts.
- If an action is unwanted, user uses Revert Action to rollback and see audit trail.

5) Approvals and Compliance
- For cronjobs with approvalRequired or conditional auto-execute, user is guided to Approvals queue to review and authorize actions.

6) Maintenance and Audit
- User uses bulk actions to clone cronjobs for templated deployments, or to adjust timezones and schedules for a group.
- Audit logs display creation, edits, runs, approvals, and reversals with timestamps and actor information.

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: (summary)
  - Cronjob: id, workspaceId, name, enabled, scheduleType, cronExpression, builderConfig, timezone, triggerType, targetType, targetId, inputTemplate, permissions, automationLevel, constraints, safetyRails, retryPolicy, outputsConfig, createdAt, updatedAt, nextRunAt, lastRunAt, lastRunStatus, meta.
  - Run: id, cronjobId, runNumber, scheduledAt, startedAt, endedAt, durationMs, status, retryCount, maxRetries, inputSnapshot, logsRef, traceRef, artifactsRef, summary.
  - RunTrace, RunLog, RunArtifact: respective structures to store traces, logs, and artifacts, linked to Run.
- API Endpoints: As listed in Backend section; all responses guarantee data integrity with safe defaults: data ?? [], Array.isArray checks, and nested optional chaining.
- Security:
  - OAuth2/JWT or session-based; RBAC policies per cronjob and per action.
  Ensure all endpoints validate user permissions; sensitive fields redacted in list views.
- Validation:
  - Cron expression syntax validation; cron builder configuration validation; required fields validation; variable binding checks with defaults.
  - Input templates validated against defined scope; if variables missing, provide actionable error.
- Null Safety Rules (CRITICAL):
  - All API results use: const items = data ?? [].
  - All arrays are guarded: (items ?? []).map(...).
  - useState initializations: useState<Type[]>([]).
  - API responses validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Optional chaining used for nested API data: obj?.property?.nested.
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

---

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] All CRITICAL runtime-safety rules are strictly followed in both frontend and backend code paths (null/undefined guards, array checks, proper initial state).
- [ ] Cronjobs dashboard can filter, search, paginate, and perform bulk actions with no runtime errors (including for empty datasets).
- [ ] Editor validates all fields in real time; invalid cron expressions or missing required vars are prevented from saving.
- [ ] Schedule Builder + Timezone handling produce correct nextRunAt values and preview windows.
- [ ] Run Details page displays inputs, traces, logs, diffs, artifacts, and timing with accurate, reversible actions.
- [ ] API layer provides complete CRUD for cronjobs, run initiation, pause/resume, clone, and revert; all responses validated and sanitized.
- [ ] Security: proper auth checks on all routes; sensitive fields masked in lists; approvals flow enforced when configured.
- [ ] End-to-end tests cover core flows: create cronjob, trigger run, inspect run details, perform revert, and approve if required.
- [ ] Performance: responsive UI with debounced search; pagination scales to large cronjob sets; efficient rendering of run traces and logs.

---

## UI/UX Guidelines

Apply the LifeOps design system consistently:
- Dark UI with dense data presentation; focus on clarity and speed for power users.
- Use the specified color palette for accents, statuses, and charts.
- Visual hierarchy prioritizes cronjob identity, next run time, and last run outcome.
- Dense but readable typography with clear spacing (8px grid, 16–20px card padding).
- Card design: rounded corners, subtle borders, soft shadows, top-left icon, bold title, then metadata.
- Navigation: left sidebar with expandable sections; top bar for breadcrumbs and global actions.
- Data Visualization: minimal charts with muted grids; series colored using teal/amber/purple accents.

---

